{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1380"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1380"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.55,0.21,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102042"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1380"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"731"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42298"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102042"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of his local rural hospital with a four-hour history of chest pain, shortness of breath and palpitations. He has never experienced these symptoms before. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears sweaty and anxious. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 118/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Heart sounds are dual with no additional sounds or murmurs. His calves are soft and non-tender. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right bundle branch block","Left bundle branch block","Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome","Posterior myocardial infarction","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003EWolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWPW syndrome is due to an underlying accessory pathway from the atrium to the ventricle \u0022bypassing\u0022 the normal AV node. As a result of this extra fast conducting pathway, a short PR interval and a pre-excitation (delta wave) is seen in the ECG. The delta waves are more prominent in the chest leads (V1-V6) and represent the early activation of the ventricle bypassing the AV node. Patients with WPW are at increased risk of having supraventricular tachycardias (SVTs) and if they have an episode of atrial fibrillation (AF), they may have a risk of a very rapid ventricular (pre-excited) response. Sudden cardiac death can sometimes occur in this cohort of patients. First-line therapy for WPW syndrome is catheter ablation therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic patients who produce ECGs with the characteristic WPW pattern do not have WPW syndrome, as the latter is reserved specifically for those who experience symptoms (e.g. palpitations, chest pain, shortness of breath). Nonetheless, it may still be appropriate to manage these patients with ablation therapy if their accessory pathway is deemed via electrophysiology studies to be \u0022high risk\u0022 or if they work in certain occupations (e.g. truck driver, airline pilot).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by a QRS duration \u0026gt;120 ms with an RSR\u0027 pattern in V1-V3 and wide S waves in leads I and V6. These features are not present in the described ECG, which instead shows the classic WPW pattern of a short PR interval and delta waves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a QRS duration \u0026gt;120 ms, broad monophasic R waves in leads I, aVL, V5, and V6, and absence of Q waves in leads I, V5, and V6. The ECG described does not demonstrate these characteristics but rather shows features consistent with WPW syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows tall R waves in V1-V2, ST depression and upright T waves in V1-V3, and reciprocal ST elevation in posterior leads (V7-V9). The patient\u0027s presentation could be consistent with myocardial infarction, but the ECG findings are more characteristic of WPW syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertrophic cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E (HCM) is an inherited condition that has been known to cause arrhythmias, syncope and lead to sudden cardiac death. ECG features of HCM may involve evidence of left ventricular hypertrophy in addition to deep Q-waves in the lateral and inferior leads. Formal diagnosis of this condition requires echocardiogram evidence of left ventricle hypertrophy in the absence of any inciting stimulus such as hypertension or aortic stenosis, with the most frequent pattern showing asymmetrical thickening of the anterior inter-ventricular septum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome is characterized by a short PR interval (\u003C120 ms) and delta waves on ECG, representing ventricular pre-excitation via an accessory pathway.","Patients with Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome are at risk of supraventricular tachycardias and potentially life-threatening arrhythmias if atrial fibrillation develops.","Catheter ablation is the first-line therapy for symptomatic Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome."],"references":["Wellens HJ. When to perform catheter ablation in asymptomatic patients with a Wolff-Parkinson-White electrocardiogram. Circulation (New York, NY). 2005 Oct;112(14):2201\u2013216. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16203931/","V\u0103t\u0103\u0219escu RG, Paja CS, \u0218u\u0219 I, Cainap S, Moisa \u0218M, Cintez\u0103 EE. Wolf-Parkinson-White Syndrome: Diagnosis, Risk Assessment, and Therapy-An Update. Diagnostics (Basel). 2024 Jan 30;14(3):296. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics14030296. PMID: 38337810; PMCID: PMC10855590. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38337810/","Chhabra L, Goyal A, Benham MD. Wolff-Parkinson-White Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Aug 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554437/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1380"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18216"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18216"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f3eb56c1-8b91-445c-829b-1fda084ee3f1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f3eb56c1-8b91-445c-829b-1fda084ee3f1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"